<HEADLINE>
<P>
ERIC DAVIS SAYS SAN DIEGO TOPS HIS LIST 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By from Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Outfielder Eric Davis, unhappy and feeling unwanted in Cincinnati, says San 
Diego tops his list of prospective new teams if the Reds don't re-sign him 
after next season. 
</P>
<P>
"The Padres are my No. 1 team right now," said Davis, who hit his 33rd homer 
Thursday in the Reds' 11-7 loss to the visiting Padres. "Why? Because of the 
ballpark they have . . . the talent they have over there, the chance to be 
contenders for a long time (and) the organization. 
</P>
<P>
"Those are things you look for when you're making a move." 
</P>
<P>
It's not certain that Davis will leave the Reds when he becomes a free agent 
after the 1990 season, but the power-hitting center fielder says he's ready for 
a change if that happens. 
</P>
<P>
"San Diego would be a great place to play," Davis said. "Ask a lot of players. 
They'll tell you they would love to go to San Diego." 
</P>
</TEXT>
