<P>
SKINNER INFORMS CHECCHI ON STUDY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Transportation Secretary Samuel K. Skinner met today with Los Angeles investor 
Alfred Checchi to disclose findings of his review of Checchi's $4-billion 
takeover of NWA Inc., parent of Northwest Airlines. 
</P>
<P>
But the Transportation Department will not comment on the meeting or on 
Skinner's findings, said Hal Paris, a department spokesman. The findings may be 
made public next week, Paris added. 
</P>
<P>
Skinner "didn't want Mr. Checchi reading about (the findings) in the paper," 
Paris said. 
</P>
<P>
Checchi could not be reached for comment after the meeting and a Northwest 
spokesman did not immediately return a phone call. 
</P>
<P>
Checchi led a group including KLM Royal Dutch Airlines that agreed during the 
summer to pay $121 a share for NWA, based in Eagan, Minn. 
</P>
<P>
Skinner has expressed concern about the foreign ownership and safety of 
airlines taken over in leveraged buyouts. Northwest, the nation's 
fourth-largest airline, was saddled with a $3.1-billion debt after the 
takeover. 
</P>
<P>
Skinner has the power to revoke the airline's operating certificate but that is 
considered unlikely. 
</P>
</TEXT>
